      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. that's helpful. u mentioned the pH level can change how fast it happens... can u go into more detail on how that works? like, specifically what's happening with the molecules during that part of the reaction?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The pH level acts like a traffic cop for the amino acids and sugars, specifically targeting the amino group (the -NH2 part) of the amino acid. In an acidic environment, this amino group gets \"protonated,\" meaning it grabs a hydrogen ion and becomes positively charged (forming -NH3+). This charged state makes the amino acid much less reactive, effectively putting a brake on the Maillard reaction.\n\nHowever, when the environment is more alkaline (higher pH), the amino group loses that extra hydrogen and stays in its free, uncharged state. This makes the amino acid far more eager to attack the carbonyl group of the sugar, speeding up the entire cascade of reactions that leads to browning.\n\nThink of it like a group of clumsy construction workers (the molecules) trying to build a bridge (the new flavor compounds) in a storm. If the wind is too strong (high acidity), they can't get a grip on their tools, and the bridge never starts. But if the wind dies down or even blows in the opposite direction (alkaline conditions), they can finally grab their hammers and start building.\n\nIn baking, adding a pinch of baking soda (which is alkaline) to your",
      "source": "target",
